SIMPLE: sicken
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sicken
<hw>Sick"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sickened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sickening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make
sick; to disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Raise this strength, and <qex>sicken</qex> that to death.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make qualmish; to nauseate; to disgust; <as>as,
to <ex>sicken</ex> the stomach</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To impair; to weaken.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sicken</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sicken
<hw>Sick"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become sick; to
fall into disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The judges that sat upon the jail, and those that attended,
<qex>sickened</qex> upon it and died.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be filled to disgust; to be disgusted or
nauseated; to be filled with abhorrence or aversion; to be surfeited or
satiated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mine eyes did <qex>sicken</qex> at the sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1337 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become disgusting or tedious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The toiling pleasure <qex>sickens</qex> into pain.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To become weak; to decay; to languish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All pleasures <qex>sicken</qex>, and all glories sink.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sickening</ent>⟦br⟧
